byline.contributor: Lilia Blaise reported from St.-Denis, and Liz Alderman and Aurelien Breeden from Paris. Reporting was contributed by Daphné Anglès and Elian Peltier from Paris, Kimiko de Freytas-Tamura and Milan Schreuer from Brussels, and Katrin Bennhold and Hannah Olivennes from London.
byline.original: By LILIA BLAISE, LIZ ALDERMAN and AURELIEN BREEDEN

abstract: Uncertainty over whether police killed Abdelhamid Abaaoud, Belgian suspected of organizing Islamic State attacks in Paris, during raid in St Denis suburb has left city wary and on edge; raid resulted in eight arrests and at least two deaths, though it is not clear whether either body belongs to Abaaoud or second suspect Salah Abdeslam.
lead_paragraph: Two people were killed and more than 5,000 rounds were fired in the raid near Paris, but officials were not sure if the suspected ringleader of the attacks was there.

headline.main: France Unsure if Raid Killed Top Suspect in Paris Attacks
headline.print_headline: Paris Is on Edge as Fate of Attacks’ Organizer Is Still a Question Mark

snippet: Two people were killed and more than 5,000 rounds were fired in the raid near Paris, but officials were not sure if the suspected ringleader of the attacks was there.
